revision.text:
'''Jewish volunteers in the Spanish Civil War''' refers to [[Jew]]s who joined [[International Brigades]] and fought in the [[Spanish Civil War]], which erupted on July 17, 1936 and ended on April 1, 1939.
==History== The fighting was between the [[Republican faction (Spanish Civil War)|Republicans]], who were loyal to the [[Second Spanish Republic|Spanish Republic]], and the [[Nationalist faction (Spanish Civil War)|Nationalists]], a rebel group led by General [[Francisco Franco]]. The Nationalists prevailed and Franco would rule [[Spanish State|Spain]] for the next 36 years. The coup was supported by military units in [[Spanish Morocco|Morocco]], [[Pamplona]], [[Burgos]], [[Valladolid]], [[Cádiz]], [[Córdoba, Spain|Cordova]], and [[Seville]]. However, barracks in important cities such as [[Madrid]], [[Barcelona]], [[Valencia]], [[Bilbao]] and [[Málaga]] did not join in the rebellion. Spain was thus left militarily and politically divided. The rebels, led by General Franco, then embarked upon an almost three-year war against the government for the control of the country. The rebel forces received support from the Third Reich, the Kingdom of Italy, and neighboring Portugal, while the Soviet Union and Mexico intervened in support of the Republican side. Other countries, such as the United Kingdom and France, operated an official policy of [[Non-intervention in the Spanish Civil War|non-intervention]].
A minority of the [[Jewish]] population, particularly that of [[Europe]], were active in [[socialist]] and [[Communist]] organisations in the period between the two World Wars.<ref>Karin Hofmeester and Lee Mitzman, ''Jewish Workers and the Labour Movement'', 2004</ref>{{Page needed|date=April 2013}}
They made up a considerable portion of the socialist volunteers, with estimates putting the figure at over ten per cent.<ref>[[Hugh Thomas (writer)|Hugh Thomas]] ''The Spanish Civil War'', 2001. p. 577n3</ref> Many of them joined the [[International Brigades]] and the [[Popular Front (Spain)|Popular Front]] to fight in the [[Spanish Civil War]] on the side of the [[Second Spanish Republic|Republicans]]. The leadership of the International Brigades considered forming an entirely Jewish brigade,<ref>Zaagsma, p 17</ref> but the high casualties made this impossible. However, a Jewish company, the [[Naftali Botwin Company]], was formed within the [[Palafox Battalion]].
At least one Jewish volunteer is known to have served with the Nationalists. Emanual Rudolph Vischer was a former [[Oberleutnant]] of the [[Swiss Army]] who had lived in Spain prior to the Civil War. The official journal of the Swiss Armed Forces reported his death in September 1936.<ref>Othen, Christopher. ''Franco's International Brigades'' (Reportage Press, 2008) p193</ref>
